The `static` keyword in programming languages has different meanings depending on the context in which it is used. Here are a few possible interpretations:

### 1. Static Variables

In the context of variables, `static` means that the variable is shared across all instances of a class. It retains its value between method calls and is initialized only once when the class is loaded.

```java
public class MyClass {
    static int myVar = 10;

    public void myMethod() {
        System.out.println(myVar);  // prints 10
    }
}
```

### 2. Static Methods

In the context of methods, `static` means that the method can be called without creating an instance of the class. It belongs to the class itself, not to any instance of the class.

```java
public class MyClass {
    public static void myMethod() {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyClass.myMethod();  // prints "Hello, World!"
    }
}
```

