Here's an example of an updated `BaseRepository` where you can find by a dynamic field. I'll be using C# and Entity Framework Core.

```csharp
public abstract class BaseRepository<T> : IRepository<T> where T : class
{
    protected readonly DbContext _context;
    protected readonly DbSet<T> _dbSet;

    protected BaseRepository(DbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
        _dbSet = context.Set<T>();
    }

    public virtual async Task<T> GetByIdAsync(object id)
    {
        return await _dbSet.FindAsync(id);
    }

    public virtual async Task<T> GetByDynamicFieldAsync(string field, object value)
    {
        return await _dbSet.FirstOrDefaultAsync(x => GetProperty(x, field).Equals(value));
    }

    protected virtual object GetProperty(object entity, string propertyName)
    {
        var propertyInfo = entity.GetType().GetProperty(propertyName);
        return propertyInfo.GetValue(entity);
    }
}
```

In the `GetByDynamicFieldAsync` method, we use the `GetProperty` method to get the property value from the entity. Then we use the `FirstOrDefaultAsync` method to find the first entity that matches the condition.

